# Documentation Standards

## Two Doc Types

1. **Tech docs** — How the system works: architecture, APIs, data models, flows. Audience: developers. Location: `docs/` (e.g. `docs/api-documentation.md`, `docs/plans/*.md`, architecture diagrams).
2. **Feature docs** — What a feature does and how to use it: user-/admin-facing behavior, configuration, examples. Audience: product, support, integrators. Location: `docs/features/` (e.g. `docs/features/access-control.md`, `docs/features/ai-query.md`).

## Requirements

- **Every functionality has documentation**: New features get at least one of: tech doc (if it changes architecture/APIs) or feature doc (if it’s user-facing). Prefer both when a feature has both implementation and usage aspects.
- **Tech doc**: Update or add sections for new services, endpoints, models, and engine behavior. Keep API docs in sync with handlers.
- **Feature doc**: Short purpose, how to use/configure, examples, and any limits or caveats.

## Structure

- **Tech**: `docs/` — `README.md` (index), `api-documentation.md`, `backend-requirements.md`, `plans/`, and any new architecture/design docs.
- **Feature**: `docs/features/<feature-name>.md` — one file per major feature; link from main `docs/README.md`.

## Example (feature doc)

```markdown
# Access Control (Column-to-Instance)

## Purpose
Control which users can read/write which databases, tables, and columns.

## How it works
Grants are stored as Permission records. The Access Engine checks them before query execution...

## Configuration
Instance-level: grant on instance. Table-level: set database, schema, table...

## Limits
Column-level enforcement uses DB GRANT where supported (Postgres, MySQL)...
```

When adding or changing functionality, add or update the relevant tech and/or feature doc.
